# Project 4. Snake

In this activity we will guide you to program a simplified version of the game Snake.
The game is an interactive program where the player chooses in which direction to move the Snake using the arrows.
When the Snakes moves, all its body goes after its head, except when it encounters an apple in its way.
In that case, the Snake eats the apple and grows a segment.
If the Snake tries to move outside the board or into its own body, the program must fail with a BOOM.
If after some time the player does not pressed any key, the Snake must continue to move in the direction of the last move.

The way to associate arrow keys with actions you can already imagine, because its similar to that in previous activities… 
For the way to indicate what to do when no key is pressed after some time, there is a special event.
Look for it, and try to deduce how it works!
Be sure to test different amounts of time -- in the machine we tested, 500 milliseconds results in an interesting play.

To represent the información we must represent every segment of the Snake. And, in order to traverse the Snake easily, each segment
must have a representation of where to find its neighbors (previous and next, towards the head and the tail, respectively). 
We will use the following representation:
  * Each segment of the Sanke is represented in a cell, using green and black stones.
  * Green stones represent the direction in which to find the next segment (towards the tail), and black stones represent the direction in 
    which to find the previous segment (towards the head).
  * Directions are represented using 1 stones for North, 2 for East, 3 for South, and 4 for West.
  * Apples are resepresented using 1 red stone.
  
A consequence of this representation is that the head is the only one with no black stones, becase it has no previous segment, and the tail
is the only one with no green stones, because it has no next segment.
Then, to know if in a given cell there is a segment of the Snake, you need to test if there are _either_ green stones _or_ black stones _or both_.

In the initial board there must be a correctly represented Snake, with the Gobstones head located over the head of the Snake. And also some apples!

To help you a bit, we give you the following primitive procedures and functions:
  * `AdvanceSnakeHeadTo_`, that given a direction, extend the head into the cell in that direction, when possible -- or fails if its not 
     possible, according to the rules.
  * `directionofLastMovement`, that used with the Gobstones head over the Snake head indicates the direction in which the Snake must move
    if no change is indicated.


We also suggest you some subtasks you will need:
  * `MoveTheSnakeTo(direction)`. To move the Snake in a given direction, the Snake head needs to be advanced, and then decide if it is needed
    to either eat the apple or advance the Snake tail (but not both).

  * `AdvanceSnakeTail`. To advance the tail, the Snake has to be traversed from head to tail, then change the representation of the tail 
    adjusting the proper stones, and then traverse back the Snake towards the head (in order for the Gobstones head to be always over the 
    Snake head when the events occur).

  * `directionOfPreviousSnakeSegment`. When this function is used on a Snake segment different for the Snake head, it describes the
    direction in which to find the previous segment -- and for that, you need to decode the direction represented with some stones!
  
  * `directionOfNextSnakeSegment`. Similar to the previous one, when used on a Snake segment different from the Snake tail, it describes
    the direction in which to find the next segment.
  
Some other subtasks that may be useful are those to gp from the Snake head to the Snake tail, and from the Snake tail to the Snake head.
You may name them `GoFromSnakeHeadToSnakeTail` and `GoFromSnakeTailToSnakeHead`, and program them as a search traversal moving to the next
or previous segment, respectively, until the destination segment is reached.

You will also need functions to ask if a cell has an apple, or the Snake head, or the Snake tail.
